<subSubSection pageId="22" pageNumber="265" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="22.[136,1452,626,1445]" pageId="22" pageNumber="265">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[136,274,626,652]" pageId="22" pageNumber="265">Description</emphasis>
(after 
<bibRefCitation author="Lansdown, R. V." box="[354,538,626,652]" pageId="22" pageNumber="265" refId="ref33002" refString="Lansdown, R. V. (2008) Water starworts of Europe. BSBI Handbook No. 11. Botanical Society of the British Isles, London, UK. 180 pp." type="book" year="2008">Lansdown 2008</bibRefCitation>
):—Stem and leaf scales present. Leaf bases connate. Lingulate leaves linear to narrowly expanded, 
<quantity box="[370,508,662,689]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.6499999999999995" metricValueMax="9.7" metricValueMin="5.6" pageId="22" pageNumber="265" unit="mm" value="7.6499999999999995" valueMax="9.7" valueMin="5.6">5.6–9.7 mm</quantity>
long × 
<quantity box="[601,738,662,689]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.5" metricValueMax="12.0" metricValueMin="5.0" pageId="22" pageNumber="265" unit="mm" value="0.85" valueMax="1.2" valueMin="0.5">0.5–1.2 mm</quantity>
wide; expanded submerged or floating leaves elliptic to more or less orbicular, 3.6–9.9(–10.3) mm long × 1.2–4.3(–4.5) mm wide, most leaves have at least part of a tertiary vein, petiole 
<quantity box="[218,331,734,761]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.25" metricValueMax="3.5" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="22" pageNumber="265" unit="mm" value="2.25" valueMax="3.5" valueMin="1.0">1–3.5 mm</quantity>
long; the apical leaves forming a floating rosette; leaves of terrestrial plants narrowly elliptic, bluntly emarginate, more or less rigid. A 
<specimenCount box="[509,530,771,797]" pageId="22" pageNumber="265" type="female">♀</specimenCount>
flower in each of a pair of axils or 
<specimenCount box="[926,947,771,797]" pageId="22" pageNumber="265" type="male">♂</specimenCount>
and 
<specimenCount box="[1002,1023,771,797]" pageId="22" pageNumber="265" type="female">♀</specimenCount>
opposed by a solitary 
<specimenCount box="[1276,1297,771,797]" pageId="22" pageNumber="265" type="female">♀</specimenCount>
, occasionally more than 
<specimenCount box="[261,332,807,833]" pageId="22" pageNumber="265" type="female">one ♀</specimenCount>
with a single 
<specimenCount box="[500,524,807,833]" pageId="22" pageNumber="265" type="male">♂</specimenCount>
. Bracts 
<quantity box="[619,756,806,833]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.5" metricValueMax="12.0" metricValueMin="5.0" pageId="22" pageNumber="265" unit="mm" value="0.85" valueMax="1.2" valueMin="0.5">0.5–1.2 mm</quantity>
long, translucent, whitish, falcate, persistent. Styles erect or slightly spreading, often poorly developed, 
<quantity box="[627,763,842,869]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.5" metricValueMax="17.0" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="22" pageNumber="265" unit="mm" value="0.95" valueMax="1.7" valueMin="0.2">0.2–1.7 mm</quantity>
long. Filament erect, 
<quantity box="[1011,1147,842,869]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.45" metricValueMax="2.7" metricValueMin="0.2" pageId="22" pageNumber="265" unit="mm" value="1.45" valueMax="2.7" valueMin="0.2">0.2–2.7 mm</quantity>
long; anthers 0.2– 
<quantity box="[1361,1452,842,869]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="22" pageNumber="265" unit="mm" value="0.5">0. 5 mm</quantity>
long × 
<quantity box="[218,355,878,905]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" metricValueMax="6.0" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="22" pageNumber="265" unit="mm" value="0.4" valueMax="0.6" valueMin="0.2">0.2–0.6 mm</quantity>
wide, quadrilocular; pollen yellow. Fruit not strumose, subsessile, higher than wide, black when mature, 
<quantity box="[228,363,914,941]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.15" metricValueMax="1.4" metricValueMin="0.9" pageId="22" pageNumber="265" unit="mm" value="1.15" valueMax="1.4" valueMin="0.9">0.9–1.4 mm</quantity>
long × 
<quantity box="[449,584,914,941]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.5" metricValueMax="11.0" metricValueMin="8.0" pageId="22" pageNumber="265" unit="mm" value="0.95" valueMax="1.1" valueMin="0.8">0.8–1.1 mm</quantity>
wide, wing mainly toward apex.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[136,1452,626,1445]" pageId="22" pageNumber="265">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,345,950,976]" pageId="22" pageNumber="265">Illustrations:</emphasis>
—Figures on pages 125 and 
<quantity box="[681,755,950,976]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.2257999999999996" pageId="22" pageNumber="265" unit="in" value="127.0">127 in</quantity>
<bibRefCitation author="Lansdown, R. V." box="[765,970,950,976]" pageId="22" pageNumber="265" refId="ref33002" refString="Lansdown, R. V. (2008) Water starworts of Europe. BSBI Handbook No. 11. Botanical Society of the British Isles, London, UK. 180 pp." type="book" year="2008">Lansdown (2008)</bibRefCitation>
; 
<figureCitation box="[984,1104,950,977]" captionStart="FIGURE 13" captionStartId="22.[136,229,2066,2088]" captionTargetBox="[290,1300,1480,2030]" captionTargetId="figure-530@22.[282,1306,1469,2041]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURE 13. The distribution of confirmed specimens of C. palustris in Oceania and Australasia" pageId="22" pageNumber="265">Figures 13</figureCitation>
(a–b) and 13A(a–b) in 
<bibRefCitation author="Mason, R." pageId="22" pageNumber="265" pagination="295 - 327" refId="ref33979" refString="Mason, R. (1959) Callitriche in New Zealand and Australia. Australian Journal of Botany 7: 295 - 327. https: // doi. org / 10.1071 / BT 9590295" type="journal article" year="1959">Mason (1959)</bibRefCitation>
. 
<figureCitation box="[225,322,986,1012]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="17.[136,229,1913,1935]" captionTargetBox="[153,1436,190,1889]" captionTargetId="figure-15@17.[151,1436,190,1889]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 10. Fruits of Callitriche in Oceania and Australasia: a—C. heterophylla, b—C. insularis, c—C. muelleri, d—C. palustris, e—C. papuana, f—C. peploides, g—C. petriei, h—C. platycarpa, i—C. sonderi, j—C. stagnalis, k—C. umbonata." pageId="22" pageNumber="265">Fig. 10d</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[136,1452,626,1445]" pageId="22" pageNumber="265">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,342,1022,1048]" pageId="22" pageNumber="265">Recognition:</emphasis>
— 
<taxonomicName authorityName="von Linne" authorityYear="1753" box="[370,500,1022,1049]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Plantaginaceae" genus="Callitriche" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="22" pageNumber="265" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="palustris">
<emphasis box="[370,500,1022,1049]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="265">C. palustris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from all other 
<taxonomicName box="[898,1106,1022,1048]" pageId="22" pageNumber="265">
<emphasis box="[898,1019,1022,1048]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="265">Callitriche</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
by the elongate fruit which are blackish when mature and winged only or more broadly at the apex, with a narrow rim at the base.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="22" pageNumber="265" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="22.[136,1452,626,1445]" pageId="22" pageNumber="265">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,345,1094,1120]" pageId="22" pageNumber="265">Distribution:</emphasis>
—Non-native. Within the region, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="von Linne" authorityYear="1753" box="[716,942,1094,1120]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Plantaginaceae" genus="Callitriche" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="22" pageNumber="265" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="palustris">
<emphasis box="[716,942,1094,1120]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="265">Callitriche palustris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been recorded in a few scattered localities in 
<collectingRegion box="[165,258,1130,1156]" country="Australia" name="Victoria" pageId="22" pageNumber="265">Victoria</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[269,372,1130,1156]" name="Australia" pageId="22" pageNumber="265">Australia</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[388,472,1130,1156]" captionStart="FIGURE 13" captionStartId="22.[136,229,2066,2088]" captionTargetBox="[290,1300,1480,2030]" captionTargetId="figure-530@22.[282,1306,1469,2041]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURE 13. The distribution of confirmed specimens of C. palustris in Oceania and Australasia" pageId="22" pageNumber="265">Fig. 13</figureCitation>
). Its native range is circumboreal, from Europe east through 
<collectingCountry box="[1164,1241,1130,1156]" name="Russia" pageId="22" pageNumber="265">Russia</collectingCountry>
, the Caucasus, the Himalayas and 
<collectingCountry box="[309,421,1166,1192]" name="Mongolia" pageId="22" pageNumber="265">Mongolia</collectingCountry>
, to 
<collectingCountry box="[459,529,1166,1192]" name="China" pageId="22" pageNumber="265">China</collectingCountry>
, the Russian Far East, the Korean Peninsula and 
<collectingCountry box="[1070,1137,1167,1193]" name="Japan" pageId="22" pageNumber="265">Japan</collectingCountry>
. In North America, it occurs more or less throughout, apart from extreme northern 
<collectingCountry box="[740,824,1202,1228]" name="Canada" pageId="22" pageNumber="265">Canada</collectingCountry>
and the south-eastern 
<collectingCountry box="[1076,1229,1202,1228]" name="United States of America" pageId="22" pageNumber="265">United States</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[136,1452,626,1445]" pageId="22" pageNumber="265">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,458,1238,1264]" pageId="22" pageNumber="265">Habitats and Ecology:</emphasis>
—There is very little information on the habitat in which 
<taxonomicName authorityName="von Linne" authorityYear="1753" box="[1114,1340,1238,1264]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Plantaginaceae" genus="Callitriche" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="22" pageNumber="265" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="palustris">
<emphasis box="[1114,1340,1238,1264]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="265">Callitriche palustris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occurs in the region. It is described as occurring in shallow, still water such as drains, ponds and dams, as well as on mud (
<bibRefCitation author="Jeanes, J. A." pageId="22" pageNumber="265" refId="ref32394" refString="Jeanes, J. A. (1999) Callitrichaceae. In Walsh, N. G. &amp; Entwisle, T. J. (Eds.) Flora of Victoria. Vol 1. Dicotyledons, Cornaceae to Asteraceae. Inkata Press, Melbourne, Australia." type="book" year="1999">Jeanes 1999</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Bean, A. R." box="[207,334,1310,1337]" pageId="22" pageNumber="265" pagination="545 - 554" refId="ref29812" refString="Bean, A. R. (2007) A taxonomic revision of Callitriche L. (Callitrichaceae) in Australia. Austrobaileya 7: 545 - 554." type="journal article" year="2007">Bean 2007</bibRefCitation>
). In its native range, it typically occurs in a wide range of seasonally inundated habitats, including wet ruts on woodland rides, turloughs, lakes, river margins, and reservoirs, as well as occasionally in permanent water bodies. 
<quantity box="[223,336,1382,1409]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.3" metricValueMax="2.6" metricValueMin="0.0" pageId="22" pageNumber="265" unit="m" value="1300.0" valueMax="2600.0" valueMin="0.0">0–2600 m</quantity>
elevation in its native range, there is no information on elevation in the region.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[136,1452,626,1445]" box="[189,858,1418,1445]" pageId="22" pageNumber="265">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,441,1418,1444]" pageId="22" pageNumber="265">Conservation Status:</emphasis>
—Least Concern (
<bibRefCitation author="Lansdown, R. V." box="[646,846,1418,1445]" pageId="22" pageNumber="265" pagination="164452" refId="ref33288" refString="Lansdown, R. V. (2016 b) Callitriche palustris. The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species 2016: e. T 164452 A 69585303. https: // doi. org / 10.2305 / IUCN. UK. 2016 - 1. RLTS. T 164452 A 69585303. en" type="journal article" year="2016">Lansdown 2016b</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
